<TEXT>
federal retirees have their eyes on 14 
billion in state income tax refunds after a us supreme court 
ruling that orders states to tax federal and state pensions equally 
or not at all 
the lawsuit filed by a michigan man who figures to save 800 a 
year on his state taxes could benefit more than 11 million 
retirees 
the state hit hardest is virginia where 200000 federal 
civilian and military retirees could be owed 150 million in 
refunds this year 
at least 20 others states could be affected according to an 
associated press survey that indicates the states could lose 461 
million a year in future revenue because of the ruling and could 
owe 14 billion if refunds for prior years are required 
about 1000 telephone calls have poured into the national 
association of retired federal employees following the march 28 
ruling said spokesman denis harrington 
theyre telling us we want our money back he said 
it was a bombshell we knew might happen and now has 
happened said oklahoma house speaker jim barker whose state 
could lose 22 million a year 
paul davis a former lawyer with the us securities and 
exchange commission who lives in east lansing said he filed the 
lawsuit in 1984 because michigan taxed part of his federal pension 
but not the pensions of state and local government retirees 
the court ruled that the retirees must be treated equally both 
taxed or both exempt and sent the case back to the michigan court 
of appeals 
i didnt anticipate the impact would be so large on states 
like virginia said davis who represented himself in the lawsuit 
states initially believed the cost would be small until they 
realized military as well as civilian pensions were involved said 
harley duncan executive director of the federation of tax 
administrators 
the word davis is the most commonly used word in state tax 
departments this week he said 
at least 21 states treat federal pensions differently from state 
and local ones according to ronald snell senior program director 
for fiscal affairs of the national conference of state legislatures 
in missouri senate appropriations chairman roger wilson said 
the 43 million annual loss and the possibility of owing 166 
million in refunds could mean a tax increase or deep cuts in the 
budget 
if youre looking for the devil with the shortest horns there 
aint one out there they are all extra long he said 
virginia gov gerald l baliles has called lawmakers back for a 
special legislative session on april 24 to deal with the issue 
which could cost the state 450 million if it is required to refund 
overpayments from prior years 
elsewhere west virginia amended its law to give federal 
retirees the same tax break as state and local retirees 
in montana a proposed measure would exempt all pension income 
from taxation oregon lawmakers created a special joint committee 
to find a solution and georgia is mulling the need for a special 
legislative session 
arizona gov rose mofford recommended taxing state and local 
retirement income on the same basis as federal 
some states including michigan and new mexico maintain that 
refunds arent required for prior years 
while states decide how to comply with the ruling the national 
association of retired federal employees is urging federal retirees 
to seek refunds for as many years as their states statute of 
limitation permits 
harrington said amended returns should be filed by this years 
state income tax filing deadline in order to preserve as many years 
as possible under the statute of limitations 
for the 1988 tax year he said retirees are being told to pay 
the tax and file an amended return 
states believed by the national conference of state legislatures 
to be affected are arizona arkansas georgia iowa kansas 
kentucky louisiana michigan mississippi missouri montana new 
mexico new york north carolina north dakota oklahoma oregon 
south carolina utah virginia and west virginia 
</TEXT>
