<TEXT>
a judge and jury agreed that the federal 
aviation administration and the pilot of a small plane were equally 
at fault for a 1986 collision of an aeromexico jetliner and the 
plane that killed 82 people 
us district judge david v kenyons decision friday absolved 
aeromexico from any responsibility in the crash 
i think when you weigh all of the possibilities the jury has 
recommended a number which is as fair and reasonable as any figure 
could possibly be he said of the 5050 division of 
responsibility 
the faa was negligent simply by its omission to warn the 
aeromexico plane said kenyon 
the judge said he was unable to determine whether the traffic 
controller walter white saw a blip on the radar screen indicating 
the small plane white has said he didnt see it 
of william kramer the private pilot who was held 50 percent 
liable for the crash kenyon said it was simply a matter of a 
caring diligent man who did not have enough flying time flying 
in what is probably one of the most difficult areas in the world to 
fly the situation simply got away from him 
the collision occurred in clear skies on aug 31 1986 as the 
aeromexico dc9 with 64 people aboard was approaching los angeles 
international airport from the east at 6500 feet 
kramer 53 with his wife and a daughter as passengers was 
flying a singleengine piper that slammed into the jets tail and 
sent both aircraft plunging into the ground all aboard both planes 
and 15 people on the ground in suburban cerritos were killed 
a national transportation safety board report said an air 
traffic controllers failure to see the small plane on his screen 
and warn the airline were factors in the accident 
the jury spent five months hearing testimony and deliberated for 
46 hours over 10 days the jurys ruling friday was binding on the 
estate of kramer but advisory on aeromexico and the faa 
damages will be decided at later trials or by settlement 
the ability of the kramer estate to pay damages is limited to 
12 million from an aviation insurance policy 
the us justice department attorney who tried the case steven 
riegel acknowledged that the government probably will wind up 
paying the majority of damages attorneys have said total damages 
could range from 50 million to 100 million 
we are disappointed that the faa was found liable for 50 
percent riegel said we are reviewing the possibility of 
appeal 
he said the air controller white has been promoted to an faa 
supervisor and is working at a control tower in another 
location 
attorney george archer representing the families of the airline 
crew relayed the comment of the mother of the jets first officer 
hector valencia 
we are all very happy and most grateful to the jury for 
exonerating the pilots and the flight crew in this terrible 
tragedy god bless them all she said in mexico city 
attorneys joseph t cook representing survivor families and 
franklin silane representing aeromexico said the verdict was not 
an indictment of the air traffic control system 
overall the traffic is safe in los angeles and the traffic 
controllers are good at the job silane said a mistake was 
made on that day 
