<TEXT>
sumptuous 15th century persian art inspired by 
the legendary mongol warlord tamerlane drawn from private and 
public collections around the world goes on display sunday at the 
smithsonian institutions arthur m sackler gallery of asian art 
the exhibition entitled timur and the princely vision was 
organized over the last five years by the sackler and the los 
angeles county museum of art where it will be shown from 
midaugust through early november after its washington engagement 
ends on july 6 
renowned for his military genius and personal charisma 
tamerlane known as timur in islamic history led an army of 
seminomadic warriors out of the central asian steppes in the late 
14th century and conquered a vast territory stretching from china 
to the shores of the mediterranean 
to solidify his dynastys political authority tamerlane and his 
princely successors embraced islamic religious and cultural 
traditions by the end of the 15th century his grandsons 
craftsmen were producing rich elaborate paintings calligraphy 
tilework metalwork ceramics and textiles that became models for 
successive islamic artisans around the world 
the sackler exhibition seeks to demonstrate the transformation 
of tamerlanes followers from crude barbaric warriors to patrons 
of some of the most brilliant and sophisticated works of art and 
architecture ever produced said curators thomas w lentz of the 
los angeles museum and glenn d lowry of the sackler 
the show includes 160 timurid paintings works in metal 
ceramics calligraphies jade and wood carvings and textiles loaned 
by 50 institutions they include the egyptian national library the 
topkapi palace museum and the turkish and islamic arts museum in 
istanbul the state hermitage museum in leningrad and the state 
treasury in the kremlin in moscow 
among the rarest objects in the show are the earliest known suit 
of islamic mail and plate armor in iron and gold lent by a saudi 
sheik and an intricately carved sandalwood box lined in red and 
gold silk which lentz said is the most luxurious and finest 
example of wood carving in the world 
another spectacular piece on loan from the kremlin is a 15th 
century cloud collar an elaborately embroidered silk 
ornamental collar for a robe two dragonhandled gold cups dating 
from the early 14th century were loaned by the hermitage museum 
which has never before displayed them publicly 
