<TEXT>
william attwood an author diplomat 
and journalist who became publisher of newsday during a career that 
spanned more than four decades has died at the age of 69 
attwood who died at home friday of heart failure served under 
presidents kennedy and johnson as us ambassador to guinea and 
kenya and as special adviser on african affairs to the us mission 
to the united nations 
attwood worked as a correspondent for the new york herald 
tribune from 1946 to 1949 first in washington then in europe and 
later in new york where he covered the united nations 
he joined colliers magazine in 1949 as european correspondent 
and also wrote a nationally syndicated column dateline your 
world 
attwood worked for look magazine from 1951 to 1961 serving as 
european editor national affairs editor and foreign editor he 
visited more than 70 countries on four continents interviewing 
such leaders as gamal abdel nasser of egypt jawaharlal nehru of 
india david bengurion of israel and josip broz tito of yugoslavia 
attwood took a leave of absence in 1960 to serve as john f 
kennedys speechwriter during kennedys presidential campaign the 
following year he was named ambassador to guinea 
he returned to cowles communications publishers of look as 
editorinchief vice president and director in 1966 he joined 
newsday as president and publisher in 1970 and was named chairman 
of the board in 1978 he retired in 1979 but continued his writing 
career 
attwood and his wife simone were among three american 
journalistcouples admitted to china in the spring of 1971 his 
reports included interviews with chou enlai and exiled prince 
norodom sihanouk of cambodia 
president carter named attwood a us delegate to the biennial 
unesco conference in paris in 1978 the following year he was named 
to the us national committee for unesco 
attwood was born in paris to american parents on july 14 1919 
he graduated with honors from princeton university in 1941 
majoring in history and politics attwood left columbia law school 
to enlist in the army in december 1941 the month the japanese 
bombed pearl harbor and brought the united states into world war 
ii he served in the middle east and the pacific 
he was author or coauthor of several books including the 
twilight struggle tales of the cold war and making it through 
middle age notes while in transit 
other writings appeared in the new yorker the saturday evening 
post readers digest the nation the new republic life time 
the atlantic harpers and esquire among other publications 
his work earned him a national headliners club award a george 
polk memorial award and a newspaper guild page one award 
attwood also lectured and taught courses in journalism at a 
numerous universities and was a member of the council on foreign 
relations the council of american ambassadors and the american 
committee on ussoviet relations 
besides his wife he is survived by a son two daughters and 
three grandchildren 
a memorial service was scheduled for tuesday in new canaan 
</TEXT>
