<TEXT>
the quality of corporate debt improved in the 
first quarter the quality of corporate debt deteriorated in the 
first quarter 
which you believe depends on which of the two major bondrating 
services you listen to 
standard amp poors corp says the quality of corporate credit as 
determined by the companys ratings of debt issues improved in the 
januarymarch period 
moodys investors service the other major debtrating service 
says that corporate credit quality continued its downward trend 
due mainly to buyouts restructurings and stock buybacks that 
affect corporate debt levels 
for the quarter sampp says it upgraded the ratings of 88 debt 
issues representing about 63 billion in debt while it downgraded 
64 issues representing about 30 billion the number it upgraded 
was about 13 times the number it downgraded 
moodys says it upgraded 32 companies representing 33 billion 
debt while it downgraded 66 totaling 47 billion moodys 
downgradetoupgrade ratio was 21to1 
one of the reasons for the vastly different snapshots of 
firstquarter debt quality is the timing of when the two ratings 
services upgrades or downgrades various debt issues 
there may be leads and lags said john lonski moodys 
senior economist 
for example moodys upgraded 39 billion in usx corp debt 
last september sampp didnt make a similar upgrade involving 5 
billion in usx debt until the first quarter thus accounting for 
some of the difference in the overall quarterly ratings improvement 
noted by sampp 
similarly some of the bonds moodys downgraded during the 
quarter may have been downgraded earlier by sampp 
as far as were concerned the first quarter had twice as many 
downgrades as upgrades lonski said last week 
kenneth c pfeil a senior vice president at sampp agreed that 
the timing of ratings changes was a factor in the differing 
interpretations of how debt fared in the first quarter 
another reason could be the subjective factor inherent in debt 
rating rating are not based entirely on hard numbers in part 
they reflect a judgment call on how a companys expected courses of 
action will affect its debt because of this variable the ratings 
of the two services can differ 
but pfeil added that he believes his firms firstquarter 
ratings picture is a fluke in an otherwise downward trend of 
corporate debt quality 
since 1982 he said there have been only three other quarters 
where sampps upgrades exceeded downgrades he said 
after this quarter well probably see the downgrades overtake 
the upgrades again i dont think weve broken the trend he said 
a companys debt rating is important because it can affect the 
price of the debt securities and the amount of interest a company 
must pay on new debt issues in order to entice investors to buy 
them 
for example when a companys debt rating drops it may find 
that it has to offer a higher interest rate on any new issues 
making them more expensive 
lonski said that though moodys believes the overall quality of 
corporate debt deteriorated in the first quarter it actually 
improved slightly from the last quarter of 1988 when moodys had 
57 downgrades to 25 upgrades for a downgradetoupgrade ratio of 
23 
about half the moodys downgrades in the first quarter reflected 
the continued concern by the credit rating companies about the 
effects of corporate takeovers and restructuring lonski said 
when one company takes over another through a leveraged buyout 
it typically takes on a huge chunk of debt from the loans and 
creditmarket issues needed to pay for the acquisition 
such debt raises concerns about the ability of the company to 
pay interest on its existing debt 
for example both ratings services downgraded the debt of rjr 
nabisco inc in the first quarter due to the 25 billion leveraged 
buyout of the atlantabased food and tobacco giant 
the other half of moodys ratings downgrades during the quarter 
reflect various factors such as increases in corporate debt due to 
other restructurings including stock buybacks lonski said 
lonski also wasnt optimistic about corporate credit quality 
improving in the near future he said he expects the wave of 
corporate takeovers and restructurings involving debt to continue 
we see no end to the situation he said 
</TEXT>
