<TEXT>
the good news is the trade deficit eventually 
will shrink the bad news is why 
the next recession which may come next year will cause a 
short sharp and temporary improvement in the trade gap by 
decreasing american demand for imported goods economists say 
increased foreign ownership of american factories also will 
shrink the deficit thats because foreign companies will supply 
the american market from factories here instead of by shipments 
from abroad 
a decline in the value of the dollar will make the deficit 
smaller but a cheaper dollar means americans money is worth less 
in world markets and foreigners can buy us assets at bargain 
prices 
managed trade is touted in washington as a way to close the 
trade gap but managing trade usually involves restricting or 
taxing imports which hurts people who buy things like 
videocassette recorders 
in summary the four main factors that should eventually narrow 
the trade deficit recession foreign ownership a cheaper dollar 
and trade policy all carry big negatives 
there is no free lunch theres no solution thats going to 
make everybody happy jeff faux president of the economic policy 
institute in washington said last week 
the trade deficit has a good side it means americans are 
consuming goods and services from abroad without being required to 
pay for them with an equal amount of goods and services created in 
the united states 
but the foreigners are accumulating ious and persistent trade 
deficits have turned the united states into the worlds largest 
debtor 
the stubbornness of the deficit was obvious last friday when the 
commerce department reported that marchs deficit had jumped 209 
percent to 105 billion 
a fresh decline in the dollar undoubtedly would help shrink the 
deficit somewhat but us policymakers are too aware of the good 
news bad news tradeoffs to favor sharp depreciation 
the american economy already running near full capacity could 
go into inflationary overheating if a dollar drop did stimulate 
exports dramatically higherpriced imports would also add to 
inflation 
moreover a cheaper dollar would make it even easier for 
japanese german british and canadian companies to buy american 
assets ranging from treasury bonds to hotels and factories 
